History of Present Illness:
___ with history of HIV/AIDS (off ___, C4 22, viral load of 
300,000 in ___, hx PCP PNA ___ 3) and ESRD on HD via tunneled 
femoral line presents with dizziness and malaise following 
dialysis today.  Per report, she had an uneventful HD session 
today and arrived home without incident. While lying down on the 
couch she had the sudden onset of weakness, lightheadedness, and 
mild sensation of room spinning. Most prominent symptom was 
weakness; patient was unable to get herself off the couch. She 
became nauseous and had one episode of NBNB vomiting. She called 
911 and when EMS arrived they had to have the fire department 
break down her door because she was unable to get up to answer 
it. Her last bowel movement was last night and normal, formed. 
No fevers, chills, night sweats, diarrhea, abdominal pain. No 
chest pain, shortness of breath, cough. Does not make urine. 
 
In the ED, initial VS were 96.6, 68, 82/64, 12, 15L nrb. Patient 
received a 500 cc bolus of NS and zosyn for empiric coverage for 
possible infection. Transfer VS were 98.5 85 132/63 22 99%. 

On arrival to the floor, patient reports a R sided headache, 
which is at baseline for her (has had chronic headaches since 
zoster infection). She still feels lightheaded, but she no 
longer has the sensation of the room spinning. She reports that 
baseline SBP's are 90's to 80's after dialysis. Of note, patient 
started pregabalin for chronic pain two days ago. She says she 
did not tolerate gabapentin due to balance problems.

Brief Hospital Course:
Ms. ___ is a ___ woman with advanced AIDS (last CD4+ 
___,000 in ___, not on ___, + OI's) and ESRD due 
to HIVAN on HD who presents with seveal hours of lightheadedness 
and subjective weakness. Symptoms were most likely due to 
Lyrica, which was stopped. 

ACTIVE ISSUES
1. Lightheadedness & Weakness: Patient's symptoms of weakness, 
lightheadedness, and malaise are most likley secondary to 
starting Lyrica given she had started the drug two days before 
symptom onset and had a similar reaction to gabapentin. Patient 
remained afebrile and had no localizing infectious symptoms 
beyond the one episode of nausea and vomiting at home. On 
admission, she had several blood pressures below her baseline 
SBP of 80's-90's, which were concerning for an atypical 
presentation of sepsis in this severely immunocompromised 
patient.  She was started on Vancomycin and Zosyn. Blood 
pressures improved with 1.5L IVF. Antibiotics were stopped and 
no further infectious symptoms/signs developed and blood 
cultures were no growth at discharge. Lyrica was stopped on 
admission and patient was advised not to take it again. 
Lightheadedness and weakness were improved at the time of 
discharge. Orthostatics were negative. 
 
2. ESRD: Due to HIVAN, on HD MWF at ___. Does not make 
urine. Patient underwent HD on ___ without complication. 

3. AIDS: Not currently no ___. Reports she received blister 
packs with ___ medications but has not started them yet. 
Followed closely by Dr. ___ as an outpatient. Patient was 
continued on azithromycin and bactrim prophylaxis. She was 
encouraged to work with Dr. ___ to restart ___ upon 
discharge.

4. Low Health Literacy: Patient demonstrated low health literacy 
surrounding her HIV and her medications. She was unsure of her 
daily medications and dosing, so medication reconciliation was 
performed based on review of OMR and recent chart notes. Patient 
would likely benefit from meeting with pharmacist for medication 
teaching as an outpatient. 

6. Right V1 Post-Herpetic Neuralgia/Headache: Patient continued 
to have pain in her right V1 distribution, which has been 
chronic since a zoster infection in that nerve. Lyrica was 
stopped as above. Although patient has ESRD, her outpatient and 
inpatient providers agreed that her neuropathic pain is 
significantly impairing her quality of life. She was started on 
low-dose duloxetine three times a week post-HD after 
consultation with her outpatient providers. 

7. Depressed Mood: No active SI. Seen by ___. Would 
benefit from outpatient Psychiatry. 

CHRONIC ISSUES
1. Eosinophilia: Dr. ___ considering ___ for 
strongyloides given patient is originally from ___. This 
acute presentation is not suggestive of strongyloidiasis, so no 
testing was performed. 

2. Paroxysmal A. Fib: Not currently anticoagulated, in sinus 
rhythm. 

3.. Social Issues: Per prior OMR notes, patient has significant 
social barriers to participation in her HIV and other medical 
care. She was seen by ___ and encouraged to 
follow-up with her outpatient SW. 

TRANSITIONAL ISSUES
- Work with Dr. ___ to resume ___ therapy with blister packs
- Encourage patient to establish with outpatient Psychiatrist
- Consider visit with ___ pharmacist for medication teaching
- Monitor for side effects on duloxetine
